Definition 2.1. Let $\mathscr{X}$ and $\mathscr{Y}$ be subcategories of a triangulated category $\mathcal{C}$. $1.$ The pair $(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y})$ is a cotorsion pair if $\mbox{Ext}^{1}(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y})=0\mbox{ and }\mathcal{C}=\mathscr{X}*% \mathscr{Y}[1]\mbox{.}$ Moreover, we call the subcategory $\mathcal{I}=\mathscr{X}\bigcap\mathscr{Y}$ the core of the cotorsion pair $(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y})$. $2.$ A t-structure $(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y})$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is a cotorsion pair such that $\mathscr{X}$ is closed under $[1]$ (equivalently $\mathscr{Y}$ is closed under $[-1]$). In this case $\mathscr{X}\bigcap\mathscr{Y}[2]$ is an abelian category, which is called the heart of $(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y})$ [BBD, BR]. $3.$ A co-t-structure $(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y})$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is a cotorsion pair such that $\mathscr{X}$ is closed under $[-1]$ (equivalently $\mathscr{Y}$ is closed under $[1]$) [Bon, P]. $4.$ The subcategory $\mathscr{X}$ is said to be a cluster tilting subcategory if $(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{X})$ is a cotorsion pair [KR1, KZ, IY]. We say that an object $T$ is a cluster tilting object if $\mbox{add}T$ is a cluster tilting subcategory.
Definition 5.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an indecomposable $2-$CY triangulated category with a cluster tilting object $T$, and $\delta(T)=n$. Assume that $0\leq d\leq n$ is an integer. A cotorsion pair $(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y})$ with core $I$ is called a $d-$cotorsion pair if $\delta(I)=d$. Denote by $CTN_{d}(\mathcal{C})$ the set of all $d-$cotorsion pairs.
Definition 1.3 (Definition LABEL:definition:joinintervals). Let $[\mathcal{U},{\mathcal{T}}]$ be an interval in $\operatorname{\mathsf{tors}}{\mathcal{A}}$. (1) We call $[\mathcal{U},{\mathcal{T}}]$ a join interval if ${\mathcal{T}}=\bigvee[\mathcal{U},{\mathcal{T}}]^{-}$. (2) We call $[\mathcal{U},{\mathcal{T}}]$ a meet interval if $\mathcal{U}=\bigwedge[\mathcal{U},{\mathcal{T}}]^{+}$.
Definition 1.1 (Definition LABEL:definition:wideintervals). We call an interval $[\mathcal{U},{\mathcal{T}}]$ in $\operatorname{\mathsf{tors}}{\mathcal{A}}$ a wide interval if $\mathcal{U}^{\perp}\cap{\mathcal{T}}$ is a wide subcategory of ${\mathcal{A}}$.
Definition 2.3 ($A_{\infty}$-natural transformation). Let $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg-functors between dg-categories. Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be an $A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformation. We call $\Phi$ an $A_{\infty}$-natural transformation if $\Phi$ is of degree $0$ and closed under the differential $d^{\infty}$ in Definition 2.2.
Definition 3.2. Two maps $f,g:\mathcal{U}\to\mathcal{V}$ between simplicial objects are called combinatorial simplicial homotopic if for each $p\geq 0$, there exist morphisms $h_{i}=h^{p}_{i}:U_{p}\to V_{p+1}\text{ for }i=0,\ldots,p$ such that the following conditions hold. 1. $\partial_{0}h_{0}=f_{p},\partial_{p+1}h_{p}=g_{p};$ 2. $\partial_{i}h_{j}=\begin{cases}h_{j-1}\partial_{i}&i<j\\ \partial_{i}h_{i-1}&i=j\neq 0\\ h_{j}\partial_{i-1}&i>j+1\end{cases};$ 3. $s_{i}h_{j}=\begin{cases}h_{j+1}s_{i}&i\leq j\\ h_{j}s_{i-1}&i>j\end{cases}.$
Definition 1.5 ([OTT81b] Definition 1.3 or [Wei16] Definition 5). Let $(X,\mathcal{R})$ be a ringed space and $\mathcal{U}=\{U_{i}\}$ be a locally finite open cover of $X$. A twisted complex consists of a graded sheaves $E^{\bullet}_{i}$ of $\mathcal{R}$-modules on each $U_{i}$ together with a collection of morphisms for $k\geq 0$ and all multi-index $(i_{0}\ldots i_{k})$ $a^{k,1-k}_{i_{0}\ldots i_{k}}\in\text{Hom}^{1-k}_{U_{i_{0}\ldots i_{k}}}(E_{i_% {k}},E_{i_{0}})$ which satisfy the Maurer-Cartan equation $\sum_{j=1}^{k-1}(-1)^{j}a^{k-1,2-k}_{i_{0}\ldots\widehat{i_{j}}\ldots i_{k}}+% \sum_{l=0}^{k}(-1)^{(1-l)(k-l)}a^{l,1-l}_{i_{0}\ldots i_{l}}a^{k-l,1-k+l}_{i_{% l}\ldots i_{k}}=0.$ Moreover we impose the following non-degenerate condition: for each $i$, the chain map $a^{1,0}_{ii}:(E^{\bullet}_{i},a^{0,1}_{i})\to(E^{\bullet}_{i},a^{0,1}_{i})% \text{ is invertible up to homotopy.}$ Morphisms and differentials are defined similarly.
Definition 1.3. Let $\mathcal{U}=U_{\bullet}$ be a simplicial object in a ringed site $(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$. A twisted complex on $\mathcal{U}$ consists of a graded $\mathcal{R}$-sheaf $E^{\bullet}$ on $U_{0}$ together with $a=\sum_{k\geq 0}a^{k,1-k}$ where $a^{k,1-k}\in\text{Hom}^{1-k}_{U_{k}}(\tau_{k,0}^{*}(E),\rho_{k,0}^{*}(E))$ and they satisfy the following two conditions. 1. The Maurer-Cartan equation $\delta a+a\cdot a=0,$ or more explicitly $\sum_{j=1}^{k-1}(-1)^{j}\partial_{j}^{*}(a^{k-1,2-k})+\sum_{j=0}^{k}(-1)^{(1-j% )(k-j)}\rho_{k,j}^{*}(a^{j,1-j})\tau_{k,k-j}^{*}(a^{k-j,1-k+j})=0;$ 2. The non-degenerate condition: $a^{1,0}\in\text{Hom}^{0}_{U_{1}}(\tau_{1,0}^{*}(E),\rho_{1,0}^{*}(E))$ is invertible up to homotopy. A morphism $\theta$ of degree $m$ from $(E,a)$ to $(F,b)$ is given by a collection $\theta^{k,m-k}\in\text{Hom}^{m-k}_{U_{k}}(\tau_{k,0}^{*}(E),\rho_{k,0}^{*}(F))% \text{ for all }k\geq 0$ and the differential is given by $d\theta=\delta\theta+b\cdot\theta-(-1)^{m}\theta\cdot a$ or more explicitly $\begin{split}\displaystyle(d\theta)^{k,m+1-k}&\displaystyle=\sum_{j=1}^{k-1}(-% 1)^{j}\partial^{*}_{j}\theta^{k-1,m+1-k}\\ \displaystyle+\sum_{l=0}^{k}&\displaystyle(-1)^{(1-l)(k-l)}\rho_{k,l}^{*}b^{l,% 1-l}\tau_{k,k-l}^{*}\theta^{k-l,m-k+1}+\sum_{l=0}^{k}(-1)^{(m-l)(k-l)}\rho_{k,% l}^{*}\theta^{l,m-l}\tau_{k,k-l}^{*}a^{k-l,1-k+l}.\end{split}$ We denote the dg-category of twisted complexes by Tw$(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R},\mathcal{U})$. If $X$ is an object in $\mathcal{C}$ we also denote Tw$(\mathcal{C}/X,\mathcal{R},\mathcal{U})$ by Tw$(X,\mathcal{R},\mathcal{U})$.
Definition 2.5 ($A_{\infty}$-quasi-inverse). Let $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg $k$-functors between dg-categories. Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be a dg-natural transformation. We call an $A_{\infty}$-natural transformation $\Psi:G\Rightarrow F$ an $A_{\infty}$-quasi-inverse of $\Phi$ if there exists $A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformations $\eta:F\Rightarrow F$ and $\omega:G\Rightarrow G$ both of degree $-1$ such that $\Psi\circ\Phi-\text{id}_{F}=d^{\infty}\eta,\text{ and }\Phi\circ\Psi-\text{id}% _{G}=d^{\infty}\omega.$ In more details, this means that we have $\Psi^{0}_{X}\Phi_{X}-\text{id}_{FX}=d\eta^{0}_{X},\text{ and }\Phi_{X}\Psi^{0}% _{X}-\text{id}_{GX}=d\omega^{0}_{X}\text{ for any }X\in\text{obj}{\mathcal{C}}$ and for any $l\geq 1$ and any $u_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(X_{i-1},X_{i})$, $i=1,\ldots,l$, we have $\begin{split}&\displaystyle\Psi^{l}(\Phi(u_{l})\otimes\ldots\otimes\Phi(u_{1})% )=\\ &\displaystyle d(\eta^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1}))+(-1)^{|u_{l}|-1}G(% u_{l})\eta^{l-1}(u_{l-1}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+(-1)^{-|u_{2}|-\ldots-|u_{l}|+l-1}\eta^{l-1}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots% \otimes u_{2})F(u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\eta^{l}(u_{% l}\otimes\ldots du_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l-1}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\eta^{l-1}% (u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{i+1}u_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\end{split}$ and $\begin{split}&\displaystyle\Phi(\Psi^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1}))=\\ &\displaystyle d(\omega^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1}))+(-1)^{|u_{l}|-1}% G(u_{l})\omega^{l-1}(u_{l-1}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+(-1)^{-|u_{2}|-\ldots-|u_{l}|+l-1}\omega^{l-1}(u_{l}\otimes% \ldots\otimes u_{2})F(u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\omega^{l}(u% _{l}\otimes\ldots du_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l-1}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\omega^{l-% 1}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{i+1}u_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\end{split}$
Definition 2.1 ($A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformation). Let $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg -functors between dg-categories. An $A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformation $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ of degree $n$ consists of the following data: 1. For any object $X\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$, a morphism $\Phi^{0}_{X}\in\mathcal{D}^{n}(FX,GX)$; 2. For any $l\geq 1$ and any objects $X_{0},\ldots,X_{l}\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$, a morphism $\Phi^{l}_{X_{0},\ldots,X_{l}}\in\text{Hom}^{n-l}_{k}(\mathcal{C}(X_{l-1},X_{l}% )\otimes\ldots\otimes\mathcal{C}(X_{0},X_{1}),\mathcal{D}(FX_{0},GX_{l}))$
Definition 4.1. A twisted perfect complex $\mathcal{E}=(E^{\bullet}_{i},a)$ is the same as twisted complex in Definition 1.3 except that each $E^{\bullet}$ is a strictly perfect complex on $U_{0}$. The twisted perfect complexes also form a dg-category and we denote it by $\text{Tw}_{\text{Perf}}(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$. Obviously $\text{Tw}_{\text{Perf}}(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$ is a full dg-subcategory of Tw$(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$.
Definition 2.4 (Compositions). Let $F$, $G$, $H:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be three dg-functors between dg-categories. Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be a dg-natural transformation and $\Psi:G\Rightarrow H$ be an $A_{\infty}$-natural transformation. Then the composition $\Psi\circ\Phi$ is defined as follows: For any object $X\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$ $(\Psi\circ\Phi)^{0}_{X}:=\Psi^{0}_{X}\Phi_{X}:FX\to GX\to HX$ and for any $u_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(X_{i-1},X_{i})$, $i=1,\ldots,l$ $(\Psi\circ\Phi)^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{1}):=\Psi^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{% 1})\Phi_{X_{0}}$ We can check that $\Psi\circ\Phi$ is an $A_{\infty}$-natural transformation. Similarly, Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be an $A_{\infty}$-natural transformation and $\Psi:G\Rightarrow H$ be a dg -natural transformation. Then the composition $\Psi\circ\Phi$ is defined as follows: For any object $X\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$ $(\Psi\circ\Phi)^{0}_{X}:=\Psi_{X}\Phi^{0}_{X}:FX\to GX\to HX$ and for any $u_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(X_{i-1},X_{i})$, $i=1,\ldots,l$ $(\Psi\circ\Phi)^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{1}):=\Psi_{X_{l}}\Phi^{l}(u_{l}% \otimes\ldots u_{1})$ We can check that $\Psi\circ\Phi$ is an $A_{\infty}$-natural transformation.
Definition 1.7. Let $\mathcal{U}$ be a simplicial object in a ringed site $(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$. Let $\mathcal{E}=(E^{\bullet},a)$ and $\mathcal{F}=(F^{\bullet},b)$ be two objects in Tw$(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$. A morphism $\phi:\mathcal{E}\to\mathcal{F}$ is called a weak equivalence if it satisfies the following two conditions: • $\phi$ is closed and of degree zero. • Its $(0,0)$ component $\phi^{0,0}:(E^{\bullet},a^{0,1})\to(F^{\bullet},b^{0,1})$ is a quasi-isomorphism of complexes of $\mathcal{R}$-modules on $U_{0}$.
Definition 3.7. For a degree $m$ morphism $\phi:\mathcal{E}\to\mathcal{F}$ in $\text{Tw}(V,\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$, we define $\Phi_{1}(\phi):f^{*}\mathcal{E}\to g^{*}\mathcal{F}$ as $[\Phi_{1}(\phi)]^{k,m-k-1}:=(-1)^{m-1}\sum_{i=0}^{k}(-1)^{i}h_{i}^{*}\phi^{k+1% ,m-k-1}.$ For $l\geq 2$ we simply define $\Phi_{l}=0$.
Definition 1.4. Let $f:\mathcal{U}\to\mathcal{V}$ be a map between simplicial object in $(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$. Then $f$ naturally induces a dg-functor $f^{*}:\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R},\mathcal{V})\to\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C},% \mathcal{R},\mathcal{U})$. In more details, for $\mathcal{E}=(E,a)\in\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R},\mathcal{U})$, $f^{*}\mathcal{E}$ is given by $(f_{0}^{*}E,f^{*}a)$ where $(f^{*}a)^{k,1-k}=f_{k}^{*}a^{k,1-k}\in\text{Hom}^{1-k}_{U_{k}}(\tau_{k,0}^{*}(% f_{0}^{*}E),\rho_{k,0}^{*}(f_{0}^{*}E)).$ For a degree $m$ morphism $\phi:\mathcal{E}\to\mathcal{F}$ we define $f^{*}\phi$ as $(f^{*}\phi)^{k,m-k}=f_{k}^{*}\phi^{k,m-k}\in\text{Hom}^{m-k}_{U_{k}}(\tau_{k,0% }^{*}(f_{0}^{*}E),\rho_{k,0}^{*}(f_{0}^{*}F)).$ By Lemma 1.1 this definition makes sense. It is clear that $\delta(f^{*}\phi)=f^{*}(\delta\phi)$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category which admits finite colimits. For a simplicial object $\mathcal{U}$ in $(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{R})$, we can construct the tensor product $\mathcal{U}\times I$ where $I$ is the simplicial set $\Delta_{1}$. Two simplicial maps $f,g:\mathcal{U}\to\mathcal{V}$ between simplicial objects are called simplicial homotopic if there is a map $H:\mathcal{U}\times I\to\mathcal{V}$ such that $f=H\circ\varepsilon_{0}\text{ and }g=H\circ\varepsilon_{1}$ where $\varepsilon_{\mu}:\mathcal{U}\to\mathcal{U}\times I$, $\mu=0,1$ are the two obvious inclusions. In this case we call $H$ a simplicial homotopy between $f$ and $g$.
Definition 2.2 (Differential of $A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformation). Let $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg-functors between dg-categories. Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be an $A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformation of degree $n$ as in Definition 2.1. Then the differential $d\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ is an $A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformation of degree $n+1$ whose components are given as follows: 1. For any object $X\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$,$(d^{\infty}\Phi)^{0}_{X}=d(\Phi^{0}_{X})\in\mathcal{D}^{n+1}(FX,GX)$; 2. For any $l\geq 1$ and a collection of morphisms $u_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(X_{i-1},X_{i})$ $i=1,\ldots,l$, $\begin{split}&\displaystyle(d^{\infty}\Phi)^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1% })=\\ &\displaystyle d(\Phi^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1}))+(-1)^{|u_{l}|-1}G(% u_{l})\Phi^{l-1}(u_{l-1}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+(-1)^{n|u_{1}|-|u_{1}|-\ldots-|u_{l}|+l-1}\Phi^{l-1}(u_{l}% \otimes\ldots\otimes u_{2})F(u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\Phi^{l}(u_{% l}\otimes\ldots du_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l-1}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\Phi^{l-1}% (u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{i+1}u_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\end{split}$
Definition 1.8. Given a defect $D$ and a bicolored $1$-manifold $M$, we define the value of $D$ on $M$ to be $D(M)\,:=\,D(N_{0})\circledast_{D(Q)}D(N_{1}).$
Definition 0.1. $\circ$ A conformal net $\mathcal{A}$ is finite if the bimodule ${}_{\mathcal{A}(I_{1}\cup I_{3})}H_{0}(\mathcal{A})_{\mathcal{A}(I_{2}\cup I_{% 4})^{\mathit{op}}}$ is dualizable as a morphism in the $2$-category of von Neumann algebras.2If $\mathcal{A}$ is irreducible, then this condition is equivalent to the conformal net having finite index, as follows. Recall from [BDH15, Def 3.1] that the index of a conformal net $\mathcal{A}$ is defined as the minimal index of the inclusion $\mathcal{A}(I_{1}\cup I_{3})\subset\mathcal{A}(I_{2}\cup I_{4})^{\prime}$. By [BDH14, Prop 7.5], if this minimal index is finite, then the bimodule ${}_{\mathcal{A}(I_{1}\cup I_{3})}H_{0}(\mathcal{A})_{\mathcal{A}(I_{2}\cup I_{% 4})^{\mathit{op}}}$ is dualizable. Conversely, if that bimodule is dualizable, then, by [BDH14, Def 5.1], its statistical dimension is finite and thus, by [BDH14, Def 5.10 & Prop 7.3], the corresponding minimal index is finite. $\circ$ A defect ${}_{\mathcal{A}}D_{\mathcal{B}}$ between finite conformal nets is finite if the action of $D(I_{1})\otimes_{alg}D(I_{3})$ on $H_{0}(D)$ extends to $D(I_{1})\,\bar{\otimes}\,D(I_{3})$, that is, if $H_{0}(D)$ is split as $D(I_{1})$-$D(I_{3})^{\mathit{op}}$-bimodule. $\circ$ A $D$-$E$-sector $H$ between defects $D$ and $E$, is finite if the the bimodule ${}_{D(S^{1}_{\top})}H_{E(S^{1}_{\bot})^{\mathit{op}}}$ is dualizable as a morphism in the $2$-category of von Neumann algebras.
Definition 1.7. A bicolored $1$-manifold is a compact $1$-manifold $M$ (always oriented), possibly with boundary, equipped with two compact submanifolds $M_{\circ},M_{\bullet}\subset M$ such that $M_{\circ}\cap M_{\bullet}$ consists of finitely many points. Moreover, each point of $M_{\circ}\cap M_{\bullet}$ should be equipped with a local coordinate $(-{\varepsilon},{\varepsilon})\hookrightarrow M$ that sends $(-{\varepsilon},0]$ to $M_{\circ}$ and $[0,{\varepsilon})$ to $M_{\bullet}$.
Definition 4. An ontological theory of quantum mechanics is epistemic if there exist states $\ket{\psi},\ket{\phi}\in H$, satisfying $0<|\braket{\psi\mid\phi}|<1$ and $D(\mu_{\psi},\mu_{\phi})<1$, where $D(\mu_{\psi},\mu_{\phi})=\sup\limits_{\Omega\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}}|\mu_{\psi}(% \Omega)-\mu_{\phi}(\Omega)|$ is the variational distance between the probability measures $\mu_{\psi}$ and $\mu_{\phi}$ associated to $\ket{\psi}$ and $\ket{\phi}$. An ontological theory is ontic when it is not epistemic.
Definition 29. Let $\Lambda$ be a measurable space with associated $\sigma$-algebra $\Sigma_{\Lambda}$. A decoherence functional is a function $\mathcal{D}\colon\Sigma_{\Lambda}\times\Sigma_{\Lambda}\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$ satisfying the following properties: • Hermitian. For all $U,V\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}$, $\mathcal{D}(U,V)=\mathcal{D}(V,U)^{*}$; • Normalisation. $D(\Lambda,\Lambda)=1$; • Finite bi-additivity. For all $U\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}$ and all mutually disjoint sets $V_{1},\ldots,V_{n}\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}$: $\mathcal{D}(U,\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}V_{i})=\sum\limits_{i=1}^{m}\mathcal{D}(U,V_{i})$ Similarly, for all $V\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}$ and all mutually disjoint sets $U_{1},\ldots,U_{n}\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}$: $\mathcal{D}(\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}U_{i},V)=\sum\limits_{i=1}^{m}\mathcal{D}(U_{i},V)$ • Strong positivity. For any $U_{1},\ldots,U_{n}\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}$, the $n\times n$ matrix $\mathcal{D}(U_{i},U_{j})$ is positive semidefinite.
Definition 11. An operational model $F$ is ontic when it maps distinct states $\psi\neq\phi$ in $\mathbf{C}$ to (anti-) distinguishable states $F(\psi),F(\phi)$ in $\mathbf{BRel}$; otherwise it is epistemic.
Definition 1. An ontological model is a Borel space1In [21], an ontological model is defined simply as a measurable space, rather than a Borel space. However, a measurable space by itself does not have sufficient structure for the properties of interest regarding ontological models. In particular, the notion of support of a measure over the space needs to be defined, see Definition 5 below. Thus we consider Borel spaces. $\Lambda$, called the ontic space. Write $\Sigma_{\Lambda}$ for its $\sigma$-algebra.
Definition 5. For a state $\psi\in H$ with ontic space $\Lambda$, let $\Lambda_{\psi}=\{\lambda\in\Lambda\mid\lambda\in U\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}\implies% \mu(U)>0\}$ be the support of $\mu_{\psi}$. An ontological theory of quantum mechanics is maximally epistemic if for all $\psi,\phi\in H$: $\mu_{\psi}(\Lambda_{\phi})=|\braket{\phi\mid\psi}|^{2}$ It is maximally nontrivial when $\braket{\phi\mid\psi}=0$ if and only if $\mu_{\psi}(\Lambda_{\phi})=0$.
Definition 9. Let $\mathbf{C}$ and $\mathbf{D}$ be operational categories with the same probabilities $\Omega$. An operational model is a functor $F\colon\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{D}$ that satisfies $F(2_{\mathbf{C}})=2_{\mathbf{D}}$ and $\langle F(\psi)\rangle_{\mathbf{D}}=\langle\psi\rangle_{\mathbf{C}}$. 2We follow the categorical/logical/model-theoretic convention that terms the domain a “theory”, and the functor a “model” or “interpretation”, rather than the physical convention where a “theory” is a class of “models”.
Definition 20. Let $F\colon\operatorname{\mathrm{CP}^{*}}[\mathbf{FHilb}]\to\mathbf{BRel}$ be a concrete operational model. An action is a map $\operatorname{\mathrm{CP}^{*}}[\mathbf{FHilb}](A,B)\times\Sigma_{F(A)}\to% \Sigma_{F(B)}$ for each $A,B\in\operatorname{\mathrm{CP}^{*}}[\mathbf{FHilb}]$, that turns a completely positive map $f\colon A\to B$ and a measurable set $U\in\Sigma_{F(A)}$ into a measurable set $f\cdot U\in\Sigma_{F(B)}$, satisfying $(g\circ f)\cdot U=g\cdot(f\cdot U)$ and $\mathrm{id}\cdot U=U$. The operational model is equivariant when $F(f\circ\rho)(*,U)=F(\rho)(*,f\cdot U)$ for all $\rho\colon\mathbb{C}\to A$ and $f\colon A\to A$ in $\operatorname{\mathrm{CP}^{*}}[\mathbf{FHilb}]$ and $U\in\Sigma_{F(A)}$.
Definition 10. Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a concrete operational category, and $\Psi\subseteq\mathbf{C}(I,A)$ a collection of states. A measurement $\chi\colon A\to 2$ anti-distinguishes a fixed state $\psi\in\Psi$ if $\langle\chi\circ\psi\rangle=0\text{,}\qquad\sum_{\phi\neq\psi\in\Psi}\langle% \chi\circ\phi\rangle=1\text{.}$ A state $\psi\in\Psi$ is anti-distinguishable within $\Psi$ if there is a measurement that anti-distinguishes it. Finally, $\Psi$ is anti-distinguishable if each $\psi\in\Psi$ is anti-distinguishable.
Definition 26. An ontological theory of quantum mechanics satisfies the preparation independence postulate (PIP), if given Hilbert spaces $H_{1}$ and $H_{2}$, with associated ontic spaces $\Lambda_{1}$ and $\Lambda_{2}$, the following are satisfied: Cartesian product assumption (CPA) Let $\{\ket{\psi}\otimes\ket{\phi}\mid\ket{\psi}\in H_{1},\ket{\phi}\in H_{B}\}$ be the set of all product states in $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$. Its ontic space is $\Lambda_{1}\times\Lambda_{1}$, with $\sigma$-algebra $\Sigma_{\Lambda_{1}}\otimes\Sigma_{\Lambda_{2}}$. No-correlation assumption (NCA) Given states $\ket{\psi}\in H_{1}$ and $\ket{\phi}\in H_{B}$, with associated measures $\mu_{\psi}\colon\Sigma_{\Lambda_{1}}\to[0,1]$ and $\mu_{\phi}\colon\Sigma_{\Lambda_{2}}\to[0,1]$, the measure $\mu_{\psi\otimes\phi}\colon\Sigma_{\Lambda_{1}}\otimes\Sigma_{\Lambda_{2}}\to[% 0,1]$ associated to $\ket{\psi}\otimes\ket{\phi}$ is determined by $\mu_{\psi\otimes\phi}(U\times V)=\mu_{\psi}(U)\mu_{\phi}(V)$ for all $U\in\Sigma_{\Lambda_{1}}$ and $V\in\Sigma_{\Lambda_{2}}$9Note that for sets $Z\in\Sigma_{\Lambda_{1}}\otimes\Sigma_{\Lambda_{2}}$ that cannot be expressed as $Z=U\times V$ with $U\in\Sigma_{\Lambda_{1}}$ and $V\in\Sigma_{\Lambda_{2}}$, we simply use the Kolmogorov sum rule, which states that for any disjoint $U,V\in\Sigma$ and any measure $\mu\colon\Sigma\to[0,1]$ it is the case that $\mu(U\cup V)=\mu(U)+\mu(V)$. Specifically, any set $Z\in\Sigma_{\Lambda_{1}}\otimes\Sigma_{\Lambda_{2}}$ can be expressed as a countable union of (cartesian) products of sets from $\Sigma_{\Lambda_{1}}$ and $\Sigma_{\Lambda_{2}}$. Knowing the value of $\mu_{\psi\otimes\phi}$ on those sets and using the Kolmogorov sum rule determines its value on any set $Z$..
Definition 18. A state-measurement duality on an operational category is a family of functions ${\dagger}\colon\mathbf{C}(I,A)\to\mathbf{C}(A,2)$. A duality-preserving operational model is an operational model between operational categories with state-measurement duality that preserves the duality: $F(\rho^{\dagger})=F(\rho)^{\dagger}$.
Definition 6. An operational category consists of: • a monoidal category $\mathbf{C}$, with tensor product $\otimes$ and unit $I$; • an object $2$ in $\mathbf{C}$, called the distinguishing object; • a set $\Omega$, whose elements are called probabilities; • a function $\langle-\rangle\colon\mathbf{C}(I,2)\to\Omega$ called evaluation.
Definition 2. An ontological theory of quantum mechanics is a theory satisfying the following: 1. Each finite-dimensional Hilbert space $H$ has an associated ontological model $(\Lambda,\Sigma_{\Lambda})$; 2. Each state $\ket{\psi}\in H$ has an associated probability measure $\mu_{\psi}\colon\Sigma_{\Lambda}\rightarrow[0,1]$ with $\mu_{\psi}(\Lambda)=1$; 3. Each orthonormal measurement $M=\{\ket{\phi_{1}},\Ket{\phi_{2}},\ldots\ket{\phi_{\dim(H)}}\}$ has a set of response functions $\{\xi_{k,M}\colon\Lambda\rightarrow[0,1]\mid 1\leq k\leq\dim(H)\}$ satisfying: $\displaystyle\forall\ket{\psi}\in H\colon$ $\displaystyle\int_{\Lambda}\xi_{k,M}(\lambda)d\mu_{\psi}(\lambda)=|\braket{% \phi_{k}\mid\psi}|^{2}$ $\displaystyle\forall\lambda\in\Lambda\colon$ $\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{d}\xi_{k,M}(\lambda)=1$
Definition 28. Let $\Lambda$ be a measurable space with associated $\sigma$-algebra $\Sigma_{\Lambda}$. A quantum measure over $\Sigma_{\Lambda}$ is a function $\mu\colon\Sigma_{\Lambda}\rightarrow[0,1]$ satisfying the following properties: • Positivity. For all $U\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}$, $\mu(U)\geq 0$; • Normalisation. $\mu(\Lambda)=1$; • Quantum sum rule. For all pairwise disjoint sets $U,V,W\in\Sigma_{\Lambda}$: $\mu(U\cup V\cup W)=\mu(U\cup V)+\mu(U\cup W)+\mu(V\cup W)-\mu(U)-\mu(V)-\mu(W)% \text{.}$
Definition 22. A signed Markov kernel from a measurable space $(X,\Sigma_{X})$ to a measurable space $(Y,\Sigma_{Y})$ is a function $f\colon X\times\Sigma_{Y}\to[-1,1]$ such that $f(-,V)\colon X\to[-1,1]$ is a bounded measurable function for each $V\in\Sigma_{Y}$, and $f(x,-)\colon\Sigma_{Y}\to[-1,1]$ is a signed measure for each $x\in X$. Signed measures have the same properties as unsigned measures, except that they can be both positive and negative. In particular, they still obey the Kolmogorov sum rule for disjoint sets. We will require that a signed measure is normalised: for all $x\in X$ it should be the case that $f(x,Y)=1$.
Definition 5.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a ($\infty$-)category with pullbacks and admitting dependent sums and products. We say that $\mathcal{C}$ satisfies the axiom $(Dep)$ if every morphism $f\in\mathcal{C}$ is contained in a class of morphisms $S$ which has a classifier and is closed under dependent products and sums.
Definition 2.7. Let $\kappa$ be a cardinal. We say that $\kappa$ is 0-inaccessible if it is just inaccessible. Inductively, for an ordinal $\alpha$ we say that $\kappa$ is $\alpha$-inaccessible if it is inaccessible and for every ordinal $\beta<\alpha$ and every cardinal $\lambda<\kappa$ there exists a $\beta$-inaccessible cardinal $\mu$ such that $\lambda\leq\mu<\kappa$.
Definition 2.3. Given a morphism $f$ in an $\infty$-category (or an ordinary category) $\mathcal{C}$ admitting pullbacks, and denoting with $f^{\ast}$ a pullback functor, we call dependent sum a left adjoint of $f^{\ast}$, and dependent product a right adjoint of $f^{\ast}$, if they exist, and in that case we write $\sum_{f}\dashv f^{\ast}\dashv\prod_{f}.$ If $f:X\to\ast$ is a morphism toward a terminal object, we will also write $\sum_{X}$ and $\prod_{X}$ respectively.
Definition 2.5. An $\infty$-category $\mathcal{E}$ is called a Shulman $\infty$-topos if it satisfies the following axioms: (S1) $\mathcal{E}$ is finitely complete and cocomplete. (S2) $\mathcal{E}$ is locally Cartesian closed, i.e. for every object $X\in\mathcal{E}$ the overcategory $\mathcal{E}_{/X}$ is Cartesian closed. (S3) There is a classifier for the class of all monomorphisms, i.e. there is an object $\Omega$ and a monomorphism $\ast\to\Omega$ such that for every object $X\to\mathcal{E}$ the map $\textup{Map}(X,\Omega)\to\textup{Sub}(X)$ given by pulling back is an equivalence. (S4) For every morphism $f\in\mathcal{E}$, there is a class $S$ of morphisms such that $f\in S$, $S$ has a classifier and it is closed under finite limits and colimits as taken in overcategories and under dependent sums and products.
Definition 3.1. Given two regular cardinals $\lambda<\mu$ we say that $\lambda$ is sharply smaller than $\mu$, and we write $\lambda\triangleleft\mu$, if the two following equivalent conditions are satisfied: (1) Every $\lambda$-accessible category $\mathcal{C}$ is also $\mu$-accessible. (2) Every $\lambda$-accessible $\infty$-category $\mathcal{D}$ is also $\mu$-accessible. (3) In each $\lambda$-filtered poset every $\mu$-small poset is contained in a $\mu$-small $\lambda$-filtered subposet.
Definition 2.2. An $\infty$-category $\mathcal{X}$ is an $\infty$-topos whenever it satisfies the equivalent conditions of 2.1.
Definition 2.6. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $\infty$-category (or an ordinary category) with pullbacks and admitting dependent sums and products. We say that $\mathcal{C}$ satisfies the axiom (DepProd) if every morphism $f\in\mathcal{C}$ is contained in a class of morphisms $S$ which has a classifier and is closed under dependent products.
Definition 6.4. A semigroup homomorphism $f:M^{\prime}\to M$ is an equivalence if there exists a homomorphism $g:M\to M^{\prime}$, called its pseudo-inverse, along with invertible conjugations $\alpha:\operatorname{id}_{M^{\prime}}\Rightarrow gf$ and $\beta:fg\Rightarrow\operatorname{id}_{M}$.
Definition 2.1. Recall that an object $C$ of a category $\mathcal{C}$ is projective if whenever there exists a morphism $f:C\to B$ and an epimorphism $g:A\twoheadrightarrow B$, there is a lifting $f^{\prime}:C\to A$ with $f=gf^{\prime}$. An object $C$ is indecomposable (or connected) if $C$ is not initial and whenever $C\cong A\sqcup B$, one of the coproduct inclusions is an isomorphism.
Definition 3.1. Recall that for toposes $\mathcal{E}$ and $\mathcal{F}$, a geometric morphism $\phi:\mathcal{E}\to\mathcal{F}$ consists of a functor $\phi_{*}:\mathcal{E}\to\mathcal{F}$ called the direct image functor, admitting a left adjoint $\phi^{*}:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ called the inverse image functor which preserves finite limits. A geometric morphism is essential if $\phi^{*}$ admits a further left adjoint, $\phi_{!}$. A point of a Grothendieck topos $\mathcal{E}$ is simply a geometric morphism $\mathbf{Set}\to\mathcal{E}$. Finally, a geometric morphism is surjective if its inverse image functor is comonadic.
Definition 6.2. Let $f,g:M^{\prime}\to M$ be semigroup homomorphisms. A conjugation1This is the author’s own terminology. $\alpha$ from $f$ to $g$, denoted $\alpha:f\Rightarrow g$ is an element $\alpha\in M$ such that $\alpha f(1^{\prime})=\alpha=g(1^{\prime})\alpha$ and for every $m^{\prime}\in M^{\prime}$, $\alpha f(m^{\prime})=g(m^{\prime})\alpha$. The conjugation $\alpha$ is said to be invertible if there exists a conjugation $\alpha^{\prime}:g\Rightarrow f$ with $\alpha^{\prime}\alpha=f(1)$ ant $\alpha\alpha^{\prime}=g(1)$; note that $\alpha$ need not be a unit of $M$ to be invertible as a conjugation.
Definition 2.5. [9, Definition 4.1] Let $n\geq 3$ be an integer. A weakly $n$-angulated category is an additive category $\mathcal C$ together with an automorphism $\Sigma$ of $\mathcal C$, and a class $\pentagon$ of sequences of morphisms in $\mathcal C$ $X_{1}\xrightarrow{f_{1}}X_{2}\xrightarrow{f_{2}}\cdots\xrightarrow{f_{n-1}}X_{% n}\xrightarrow{f_{n}}\Sigma X_{1},$ called $n$-angles, satisfying the following axioms: ${\rm(F1^{\prime})}$. For each $X\in\mathcal C$, the sequence $X\xrightarrow{1_{X}}X\xrightarrow{0}\longrightarrow\cdots\longrightarrow 0% \longrightarrow\Sigma X$ belongs to $\pentagon$. The class $\pentagon$ is closed under taking direct sums and direct summands. ${\rm(F2)}$. A sequence $X_{1}\xrightarrow{f_{1}}X_{2}\xrightarrow{f_{2}}\cdots\xrightarrow{f_{n-1}}X_{% n}\xrightarrow{f_{n}}\Sigma X_{1}$ of morphisms in $\mathcal C$ is in $\pentagon$ if and only if so is $X_{2}\xrightarrow{f_{2}}\cdots\xrightarrow{f_{n-1}}X_{n}\xrightarrow{f_{n}}% \Sigma X_{1}\xrightarrow{(-1)^{n}\Sigma f_{1}}\Sigma X_{2}$. ${\rm(F3)}$. For each commutative diagram $\xymatrix@M=1mm{X_{1}\ar[r]^{f_{1}}\ar[d]^{h_{1}}&X_{2}\ar[r]^{f_{2}}\ar[d]^{h% _{2}}&X_{3}\ar[r]^{f_{3}}\ar@{..>}[d]^{h_{3}}&\cdots\ar[r]^{f_{n-1}}&X_{n}\ar@% {..>}[d]^{h_{n}}\ar[r]^{f_{n}}&\Sigma X_{1}\ar[d]^{\Sigma h_{1}}\\ Y_{1}\ar[r]^{g_{1}}&Y_{2}\ar[r]^{g_{2}}&Y_{3}\ar[r]^{g_{3}}&\cdots\ar[r]^{g_{n% -1}}&Y_{n}\ar[r]^{g_{n}}&\Sigma Y_{1}\\ }$ with rows in $\pentagon$, there exists maps $h_{i}:{}X_{i}\longrightarrow Y_{i}$ for $3\leqslant i\leqslant n$ making the diagram commute. In other words, any such diagram can be completed to a morphism of $n$-angles.
Definition 3.1. Let $(\Lambda,\mathcal{E})$ be a locally finite $R$-algebra. We say that $\{T_{i}^{\bullet}\}$ is a locally finite tilting complex set if the following conditions are satisfied: $(1)$ $T_{i}^{\bullet}\in{\mathscr{K}}^{b}(\Lambda\mbox{{\rm-proj}})$ for each $i\in\mathcal{I}$; $(2)$ ${\rm Hom\,}(T_{i}^{\bullet},T_{j}^{\bullet}[n])=0$ for $n\neq 0$ and $i,j\in\mathcal{I}$; $(3)$ ${\rm thick}(T_{i}^{\bullet},i\in\mathcal{I})={\mathscr{K}}^{b}(\Lambda\mbox{{% \rm-proj}})$.
Definition 2.4. Let $\mathcal C$ be an additive category, and let $\mathcal D$ be a full additive subcategory of $\mathcal C$. A sequence $X\xrightarrow{f_{0}}D_{1}\xrightarrow{f_{1}}\cdots\xrightarrow{f_{n-1}}D_{n}% \xrightarrow{f_{n}}Y\quad\quad(\star)$ in $\mathcal C$ is called a symmetric $\mathcal D$-approximation sequence if the following three conditions are satisfied. $(1)$ The sequence $D_{1}\xrightarrow{f_{1}}\cdots\xrightarrow{f_{n-1}}D_{n}\xrightarrow{f_{n}}Y$ is a right $\mathcal D$-approximation sequence in $\mathcal C$; $(2)$ The sequence $X\xrightarrow{f_{0}}D_{1}\xrightarrow{f_{1}}\cdots\xrightarrow{f_{n-1}}D_{n}$ is a left $\mathcal D$-approximation sequence in $\mathcal C$; $(3)$ The morphism $f_{0}$ is a weak kernel of $f_{1}$ and the morphism $f_{n}$ is a weak cokernel of $f_{n-1}$.
Definition 1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category, let $\boldsymbol{X}=\left(X_{\lambda},p_{\lambda\lambda^{\prime}},\Lambda\right)$ and $\boldsymbol{Y}=(Y_{\mu},q_{\mu\mu^{\prime}},M)$ be inverse systems in $\mathcal{C}$ and let $J=(J,\leq)$ be a directed partially ordered set. A $J$-morphism (of $\boldsymbol{X}$ to $\boldsymbol{Y}$ in $\mathcal{C}$) is every triple $(\boldsymbol{X},(f,(f_{\mu}^{j})),\boldsymbol{Y})$, denoted by $(f,f_{\mu}^{j}):\boldsymbol{X}\rightarrow\boldsymbol{Y}$, where $(f,(f_{\mu}^{j}))$ is an ordered pair consisting of a function $f:M\rightarrow\Lambda$, called the index function, and, for each $\mu\in M$, of a family $(f_{\mu}^{j})$ of $\mathcal{C}$-morphisms $f_{\mu}^{j}:X_{f\left(\mu\right)}\rightarrow Y_{\mu},$ $j\in J,$ such that, for every related pair $\mu\leq\mu{}^{\prime}$ in $M$, there exists a $\lambda\in\Lambda,$ $\lambda\geqslant f(\mu),f\left(\mu^{\prime}\right)$, and there exists a $j\in J$ so that, for every $j^{\prime}\geqslant j$, $f_{\mu}^{j^{\prime}}p_{f(\mu)\lambda}=q_{\mu\mu^{\prime}}f_{\mu^{\prime}}^{j^{% \prime}}p_{f(\mu^{\prime})\lambda}$. If the index function $f$ is increasing and, for every pair $\mu\leq\mu^{\prime}$, one may put $\lambda=f(\mu^{\prime})$, then $(f,f_{\mu}^{j})$ is said to be a simple $J$-morphism. If, in addition, $M=\Lambda$ and $f=1_{\Lambda}$, then $(1_{\Lambda},f_{\lambda}^{j})$ is said to be a level $J$-morphism. Further, if the equality holds for every $j\in J$, then $(f,f_{\mu}^{j}):\boldsymbol{X}\rightarrow\boldsymbol{Y}$ is said to be a commutative $J$-morphism. (If there exists $\min J\equiv j_{\ast}$, the commutativity means that one may put $j=j_{\ast}$.)
Definition 2. A $J$-morphism $(f,f_{\mu}^{j}):\boldsymbol{X}\rightarrow\boldsymbol{Y}$ of inverse systems in $\mathcal{C}$ is said to be equivalent to a $J$-morphism $(f^{\prime},f_{\mu}^{\prime j}):\boldsymbol{X}\rightarrow\boldsymbol{Y}$, denoted by $(f,f_{\mu}^{j})\sim(f^{\prime},f_{\mu}^{\prime j}),if$ every $\mu\in M$ admits a $\lambda\in\Lambda$, $\lambda\geqslant f(\mu),f^{\prime}(\mu)$, and a $j\in J$ such that, for every $j^{\prime}\geq j$, $f_{\mu}^{j^{\prime}}p_{f(\mu)\lambda}=f_{\mu}^{\prime j^{\prime}}p_{f^{\prime}% (\mu)\lambda}$.
